



	MicroEMACS - a screen editor.      (on the Atari ST)
	=============================
	
	Source code by David G. Conroy, substantially modified
	by Moshe Braner.  See copyright notice in file 'main.c'.
	This misleading document by Moshe Braner,  860624.

	General mood
	------------

	MicroEMACS is a full-screen editor suitable for editing
	program files, or for post-formatted word processing as
	with proff. To invoke microEMACS, type 'me [filename]'.
	(From the desktop, double click me.ttp & enter filename.)
	To exit, press CTRL-Z (or CTRL-C to avoid writing the
	file back).

	MicroEMACS is essentially a one-mode editor, so that all
	commands are invoked via function keys or command key
	sequences, e.g. Control, Esc, or Alternate. Effort has
	been made to make use of labeled function keys and
	mnemonics. (See accompanying F-keys label maker.)
	MicroEMACS can edit one or more files in one or more
	screen windows.  All editing is done on a copy of the
	file in RAM, so the maximum file size is somewhat
	limited.  The last line on the screen is for messages
	and some user input, and the last line of each window
	shows the buffer name, file name, whether it may be
	changed (+), and whether it has been changed (*).

	MicroEMACS keeps track of two special positions: the
	'point' and the 'mark'. The point is where the cursor is,
	while the mark is invisible. Some commands set the mark
	or manipulate the block of text between the point and the
	mark, known as the 'region'.

	MicroEMACS commands are of several types, which will here
	be denoted as follows: ('Q' is just an example)

	C-Q means holding down the <Control> key and pressing Q,
	A-Q means holding down the <Alternate> key and pressing Q,
	S-Q means holding down the <Shift> key and pressing Q,
	E-Q means pressing the <Esc> key and then pressing Q,
	C-X Q means a C-X sequence followed by the Q key.
	Other combinations are also used.

	Some commands take a prescribed numerical argument,
	which is 1 by default. Press <Esc> and then the number
	(or '-' for -1), then the command key. Alternatively,
	use the C-U 'argument command'.  Press C-U and then
	enter the number, or use the default of '4'. Repeating
	C-U multiplies the argument by 4.  For example, C-U C-U
	<Insert> opens 16 blank lines.

	'Kill' commands (e.g. Cut and Copy) save the text they
	kill in a 'kill buffer', from which it can be 'yanked'
	back to the same or other positions in the file. 
	('Deleted' text is lost, though.) To undo a kill just
	done, press <Undo>.







	Cursor control commands
	-----------------------

	Keypad arrows: move cursor by characters/lines.
	<Shift> horizontal arrows: move by words.
	<Shift> vertical arrows: scroll window relative to text.
	<Esc> vertical arrows: move by paragraph.
	<Control> horiz arrows: move to beginning/end of line.

	F8:  scroll up a screenfull.
	F9:  scroll down a screenfull.

	F10:  set the MARK at current cursor position.
	A-F10:  exchange mark and cursor  (Also A-X).
	E-G or A-G: goto line number (precede with argument).

	E-<Clr/Home>: move to beginning of file.
	C-<Clr/Home>: move to end of file


	Kill, delete and insert
	-----------------------

 	<Backspace>: Delete previous character.
	<Delete>:    Delete current character.
	   With <Shift> or <Control>: to beginning/end of line.
	   Preceded by <Esc>: Kill word by word.

	<Tab>:       Insert a tab character.
	   With numerical argument: set tab size.
	<Return>:    Insert a newline.
	C-<Return>:  Insert a newline and indent.
	<Insert>:    Insert blank line.
	   With <Shift> or <Control>: Kill blank lines.

	F4:    Kill to end of line, or kill line break if at end.
	A-F4:  Cut (kill, wipe) region between mark and cursor.
	F5:    Paste contents of Kill Buffer back, at cursor
	A-F5:  Copy region to Kill Buffer

	<Undo>   Undo the Kill, Cut or Paste just done.
	A-<Undo> Flush Kill Buffer into a buffer called '[]'.
 

	Searches
	--------

	F7  Search forward. Type in a string to be searched for, end
	    it with <Esc> (or with C-C to ignore case differences).
	    A '?' matches any one character, C-W matches any amount
	    of white space (including none).
 
	F6  As above, but Reverse search from cursor position back.
 
	A-F7 or A-)  Search forward for complementing brace.
	             (A 'brace': (), [], {}.)
	A-F6 or A-(  Same - backwards.









	Window control
	--------------

	Many WINDOWS may be active at once on the screen. 
	Windows may show different parts of the same buffer,
	or may display different buffers.

	F8    Scroll window up by a windowfull.
	F9    Scroll window down by a windowfull.
	A-2   Split current window in two.
	A-1   Remove all but current window.
	A-N   Move cursor to next window.
	A-P   Move cursor to previous window.
	A-^   Enlarge current window.
	A-F8  Scroll other window up.
	A-F9  Scroll other window down.
	<Shift> vertical arrows: Scroll window one line.
	<Clr/Home>  Scroll current line to top (or <argument>)
	            window position.


	Extra editing commands
	----------------------

	C-T  Transpose this and previous characters.
	A-T  Transpose this and previous lines.
 
	E-U  UPPERCASE word.
	E-L  lowercase word.
	E-C  Capitalize word.

	C-X C-U  Convert region into UPPERCASE.
	C-X C-L  Convert region into lowercase.
 
	C-Q or E-Q  Quote next char (even ctrl) into text.
	A-A  Enter the next char with MSB set (see altchars.doc).
	     (Non-ASCII characters, will not print as-is.)

	A-R  Set right margin (column for wordwrap).
	A-L  Set left margin.
	        (Precede these with a numerical argument.)
	A-F  (Re)Format paragraph so that text lies between
	         margins (with argument: double spaced).


	File/buffer/program control
	---------------------------

	A BUFFER is a named area containing a document being
	edited.  Many buffers may be activated at once. Each
	buffer has a name, which is typically the lowercased
	disk filename of the document it contains.

	F2     Switch to another buffer, by name.
	        (default [appears in brackets]: previous one)
	A-K    Kill a non-displayed buffer

	S-<Help>: List current buffers








	C-X C-B   Enter a new name for current buffer
	C-X C-F   Enter a new default File name for buffer

	A-S   Save current buffer to disk, using the buffer's
	      filename as the name of the disk file. Any disk
	      file of that name will be overwritten.

	A-F2  Visit a file. (Also A-V.)  Read it into a new
	      buffer. Flag as view-only (A-E to edit).

	F3    Read a file into the current buffer, erasing its
	      previous contents. No new buffer will be created.
	      Flag as editable (A-E to protect).

	A-F3  Write current buffer to disk. Type a filename at
	      the prompt, or hit Return for the default.

	A-D   List contents of directory.
	A-C   Change the default directory.

	C-Z   Quit, saving file if changed.
	C-C   Quit without saving, after confirmation.


	Other commands
	--------------
 
	Undo   Cancel current command and return to top level of
	       processing. (Also undoes a kill, cut or paste.)

	<Esc> #  (or C-U #, with default of 4) - Enter a numerical
	         argument ('-' = -1).

	A-F1 (or A-M)  Begin/End a macro definition:
	               execute AND store the keystrokes.
	F1     Execute the defined macro.

	A-=  Display column number, line number, ASCII code,
	       and position in file (in characters and percent)
	A-E  Toggle between edit & view-only modes
	A-I  Toggle between insert & overstrike modes
	A-Q  Toggle visibility of white-space characters (spaces
	       show as "_", tabs as "--->", and newlines as "<<")
